description.value: Sandstone statue of Ramses II: the lower half of a standing statue of Ramses II holding a standard. The statue base is itself on a smaller plinth. The prenomen and nomen of Ramses II and epithets are incised on the king's skirt, the base of the statue, the standard, the back pillar and along the sides of the base together with the names of Hathor, lady of turquoise, and Thoth, lord of Punt, who are also named on the top of the base . On the left side of the statue behind the standard, the figure of Queen Bintanat is carved in sunk relief. Her name is  wrongly   written. Fragment A supplies the head for the figure of the queen and part of the back pillar. Fragment B is a portion of the standard with part of the prenomen and epithets.

description.value:
Fragmentary sandstone standing statue of Ramses II, only the lower legs, base and part of the arm and standard now remaining.

The king is depicted in a striding position with the left leg advancing ahead of the right, and he wears a long kilt with a pleated front panel. A row of uraeus cobras and a column of incised text are carved across his clothing, with deliberate damage to the upper portion of the text. An underlayer of thin material is visible across his feet, and he wears carefully carved sandals. At his feet are four short columns of text consisting of royal names and titles. At his left side he holds a standard, the lower portion intact and also inscribed with a column text. Behind the standard a small female figure of Queen Bintanat is depicted in sunken relief. description.value: Terracotta figure of Athena Dadouchos.  Athene Dadouchos, standing, holding a large torch to her right side, and supporting an oval shield with her lowered left hand. She wears a medium-length girt chiton with overfall, and an aegis: the gorgoneion is very worn. Her hair is parted in the centre and is brushed back over her ears, and she has a crested helmet with chevron decoration on its face above the brim, with a raised circle on the front of the plume-holder; lappets fall onto her shoulders from below the helmet. The shield, which has a ring-shaped boss, rests on an object now incomplete, perhaps an altar: its lower part, together with Athene’s feet and the plinth, are lost. The back is largely plain, only the helmet plume being indicated. A hole at the top of the torch has signs of burning, showing its use as an incense-holder.   Hollow; two-piece mould. Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt, with traces on the front of a white dressing.

description.value:
Feldspar and gilded seated figure of the goddess Isis suckling Horus-the-Child (Harpocrates), with a separate inscribed base made of green breccia.

Isis wears a long smooth wig topped with a modius crown. At her forehead is a circular hole which was likely used to fit a uraeus ornament, possibly made from a separate material. Her hollow eyes bear traces of blue paint and were likely originally inlaid. The eyebrows are heavily arched and there is a heavy ridge delineating the upper eyelids, with short cosmetic lines at the outer corners of the eyes. Her nose is slim and her mouth is small in size, while her jawline is fleshy and rounded. There is little suggestion of her neck and the shoulders are raised high, creating a slightly hunched appearance of the upper body. She wears a long sheath dress, and Horus-the-Child (also known as Harpocrates) is shown as a naked infant resting on his mother’s lap. Isis cradles his head and offers him her breast, and gilded detail is visible … (See Merlin record for full description)

description.value: Irregular bulla made of a fine brown Nile clay in the shape of a ball. The object is very roughly formed and finished, the surface is irregular as well as very eroded and partly chipped off, there are white accretions as well as black discolouration on the surface. There are five possibly six seal impressions of an oval scarab-like seal with a very flat cut motif that is almost unrecognisable anymore. One of the impressions shows a circumferential line with two signs, a straight thick line as well as a sign that consists of two perpendicular bands meeting in a right angle (L-shape). The seal has the size of about 1.2 x 1.0 cm. After excavation a glossy translucent substance was added for consolidation.

description.value: Terracotta figure of Sarapis: there is some superficial damage but the figure is well preserved. This piece was manufactured in two separate halves, the back unmodelled. The subject is a seated, bearded male holding a cornucopia in his left arm and clutching the arm of the throne with his right arm. On his head is an Egyptianizing lotus crown. These attributes are commonly associated with the god Sarapis. The body is well modelled, the torso exposed, with drapery covering the legs.

description.value: Terracotta figure of Sarapis enthroned, with Harpokrates. There is some superficial damage but the figure is well preserved. This piece was manufactured in two separate halves, the back unmodelled. Sarapis seated on a throne, himation over his lower limbs and his upper body bare. He wears a reeded atef crown, with disc and twisted horns. He is bearded. A cornucopia is held in the crook of his left arm and he rests his right hand (which on more complete examples holds a small phiale) on the head of Harpokrates, who leans with his legs crossed against the arm of the throne. The details of Harpokrates are obscure and damaged, but he has his finger to his mouth and apparently has a shaven head with a side-lock. He also appears to be naked, except for a himation over his left shoulder. The throne has details of its construction on its top edge and its legs. Curved flat-fronted plinth. Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt. Traces of a white dressing on the front. The atef crown and cornucopia are attributes commonly associated with the god Sarapis. The body is well modelled.

description.value: Limestone stelophorous statue of an unnamed man: the deceased is represented kneeling on a pedestal and holding before him a stela. He wears a long braided wig, a short beard and a long skirt reaching to the ankles. The top of the stela is shaped in the form of an offering-table, some of the offerings being carved on the top of the support connecting the stele with the figure. In the arch are incised two 'wedjat'-eyes flanking a 'shen' sign, a cup and three lines of water. Below, incised in eight horizontal lines of Middle Egyptian, is a hymn to the sun-god (one of those now designated Spell 15 of the funerary Book of the Dead). The name of the owner has been erased, but otherwise both figure and stela are well preserved. Traces of red paint still remain on the body.

description.value: East Greek terracotta figure vase (plastic vase). Complete vase, minus parts of rim, in the form of a seated kore (Greek maiden). She sits on a throne with a footstool, hands on knees. She wears a low stephane and headband behind long curly hair parted centrally and resting on her shouldars. She wears a red chiton and symmetrical himation covering her head, back, sides and hanging in folds from the knees. The modelling is sketchy. She has almond shaped eyes. Traces of black paint on hair and throne, and red paint on clothes and rim. White coating under some of the red paint, though in other areas white residue appears to be post depositional. Orange-brown fine Milesian clay fabric with abundant fine mica and rare white inclusions.

description.value: Light grey limestone statuette of a lion, painted. Lion seated on a small rectangular plinth. The tail is curling around the right hind leg, the front legs are very sturdy. The face is expressive with small, rather narrow, eyes (with traces of black paint); the mouth is slightly open, revealing the teeth with the red painted tongue protruding. The mane is worked flat and appears to be collar-like. There is a break through the frontpaws, belly and hind quarters; ears, head, and chin are chipped.

description.value: Light grey limestone statuette of a youth of Cypro-Ionian style, painted.  Draped youth standing on a curved plinth, playing a lyre; the left hand holds the instrument, the right hand, across the body, touches it with a plectrum. The head, parts of the shoulders and the front of the lyre are missing.  He is wearing a tight long chiton with an overfold at the waist; the lower half of the garment is pleated in small tight folds in the front, covering the legs down to the calves, at the centre there is a neat bunch of folds, with a tanged lower edge, the outline of the legs is visible below the chiton; the cloth covering his upper body is tight, straight and may either be part of the chiton distinguished from the lower half by an overfold or a separate piece of clothing; across the upper body a cloak is painted in red, as are his boots. The sounding-board of the lyre is painted red, the strings black.  Long slender proportions; rounded section; the back is rounded and indicates the motion, however, it is not worked to the same degree of detail as the front with the folds for instance not indicated. The left foot slightly advanced; the right upper arm is separated from the body.

description.value: Bronze standing figure of Khonsirdis: he is shown here as a priest with a shaven head and a leopard-skin vestment. In his proper left hand he holds the base of a statue that he supported with his right hand. That figure, made separately, is now lost but it was undoubtedly an image of Osiris. Khonsirdis's figure is covered with a wealth of incised detail, but apart from silver inlay in the eyes, there is apparently no evidence of precious metal inlays. On his proper right shoulder is a cartouche of Psamtek I and above his right breast a figure of Osiris in profile facing right. The leopard skin is here clearly an imitation, probably in cloth: the spots are shown as rows of circles, the "paws" are neatly fitted at the hips, and the tail hangs down behind. A band over the left shoulder, of a kind frequently represented on these vestments during the Twenty-fifth and Twenty-sixth Dynasties, gives Khonsirdis' names and titles and again names his king. Although his long kilt is elaborately pleated and has a stiffened front panel, it is narrow and relatively simple, more in the style of the Middle Kingdom than the New Kingdom. A narrow strip down the centre of the panel continues Khonsirdis' inscription, interrupted by a vignette that shows him worshiping Osiris. Thus the figure he held must have represented that god. Since there seems to have been relatively little modeling, as opposed to engraved detail, the figure's large navel and the trench-like depression leading down to it are very noticeable, though these details would have been largely hidden when the image of Osiris was in place. The figure's broad shoulders and long limbs increase the sense of monumentality in this large bronze.
